512126,0.03525685,-0.00551357,-0.01494285,0.03903035,0.08659615,0.02692739,-0.06346043,-0.01049505,0.04109055,-0.01847885,-0.01020178,-0.02936538,0.01727574,0.04122464,0.00018842,-0.00765900,-0.05932833,0.01057477,0.01658830,0.01468086,0.08771502,-0.04883347,-0.04199379,-0.06185631,-0.03332404,0.02605289,-0.01125520,-0.02688235,0.01535131,-0.08697907,0.02759116,0.00224689,-0.01980625,0.01395111,-0.03612359,0.00518754,0.01880464,-0.02477712,0.02140366,-0.04319932,0.04098162]',E'Sharing data between components {/*sharing-data-between-components*/}\n\nWhen you click the button, the `onClick` handler fires. Each button''s `onClick` prop was set to the `handleClick` function inside `MyApp`, so the code inside of it runs. That code calls `setCount(count + 1)`, incrementing the `count` state variable. The new `count` value is passed as a prop to each button, so they all show the new value. This is called "lifting state up". By moving state up, you''ve shared it between components.\n\n<Sandpack>\n\n```js\nimport { useState } from ''react'';','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Index", "section_title": "index", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/index.md", "topics": "react,hooks,index", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
