,0.00952130,0.02441495,0.03653193,-0.04285794,0.02257728,0.07024752,0.05355716,-0.02233060,0.00275380,0.02480759,0.00925796,0.00061694,-0.05832638,-0.01225237,0.00445697,0.02252837,-0.06108731,-0.01627614,0.00687223,-0.03171348,0.01651909,0.02988960,-0.02496715,0.02464523,-0.03072807,-0.06306836,-0.02205460,-0.01816840,-0.03589186,-0.01836219,-0.04247786,-0.00846045,-0.00516520,0.00059110,0.00381091,-0.05364333,0.07135908,0.05299161,-0.03130293,0.01430593,0.04615122,-0.02057381]',E'Forwarding props with the JSX spread syntax {/*forwarding-props-with-the-jsx-spread-syntax*/}\n\nThere''s nothing wrong with repetitive code—it can be more legible. But at times you may value conciseness. Some components forward all of their props to their children, like how this `Profile` does with `Avatar`. Because they don''t use any of their props directly, it can make sense to use a more concise "spread" syntax:\n\n```js\nfunction Profile(props) {\n  return (\n    <div className="card">\n      <Avatar {...props} />\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Passing Props To A Component", "section_title": "passing-props-to-a-component", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/passing-props-to-a-component.md", "topics": "react,hooks,passing,props,to,a,component", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
