4000,0.03429018,0.06399409,0.02304201,-0.03625482,-0.00476991,0.11792419,0.01911028,0.01352918,-0.05071668,0.02337087,0.00536412,-0.00395147,-0.06128217,0.03746127,0.05249236,0.04422013,-0.01675938,-0.03152229,0.03201706,-0.00713153,-0.03164269,0.03889861,-0.02273478,-0.01744492,-0.05512336,-0.02954252,0.03400329,-0.06192958,-0.02875091,-0.00939056,0.01877001,0.03909662,0.02317518,0.01759649,0.01363704,-0.04466205,0.02463331,0.04799282,0.00668324,0.05768802,0.02440224,0.03888085]',E'Adding event handlers {/*adding-event-handlers*/}\n\nBy convention, it is common to name event handlers as `handle` followed by the event name. You''ll often see `onClick={handleClick}`, `onMouseEnter={handleMouseEnter}`, and so on.\n\nAlternatively, you can define an event handler inline in the JSX:\n\n```jsx\n<button onClick={function handleClick() {\n  alert(''You clicked me!'');\n}}>\n```\n\nOr, more concisely, using an arrow function:\n\n```jsx\n<button onClick={() => {\n  alert(''You clicked me!'');\n}}>\n```','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Responding To Events", "section_title": "responding-to-events", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/responding-to-events.md", "topics": "react,hooks,responding,to,events", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
