546,0.01857863,0.07191844,-0.01325442,-0.02683305,-0.01860352,0.10901693,0.04176410,-0.00523068,-0.02958991,0.04690973,-0.00360297,-0.03834806,-0.07621829,0.01839980,0.05187741,0.01068032,-0.02717667,-0.02672055,0.04948375,0.00393706,-0.03452974,0.01528887,-0.08521791,-0.05482222,-0.02458437,-0.03241488,0.03334067,0.05304146,0.01512626,-0.00042117,-0.07893353,0.00864567,0.03349859,0.00807009,0.00832190,-0.01013325,0.01649745,0.07687899,-0.02163217,0.04460253,0.00586151,0.07573510]',E'Passing event handlers as props {/*passing-event-handlers-as-props*/}\n\nFinally, your `Button` component accepts a prop called `onClick`. It passes that prop directly to the built-in browser `<button>` with `onClick={onClick}`. This tells React to call the passed function on click.\n\nIf you use a [design system](https://uxdesign.cc/everything-you-need-to-know-about-design-systems-54b109851969), it''s common for components like buttons to contain styling but not specify behavior. Instead, components like `PlayButton` and `UploadButton` will pass event handlers down.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Responding To Events", "section_title": "responding-to-events", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/responding-to-events.md", "topics": "react,hooks,responding,to,events", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
