420,0.01899396,0.07280998,-0.00744685,-0.00059215,0.00131805,0.08555025,0.04297677,0.02972122,-0.07073782,0.02804635,0.02094653,-0.04731206,-0.06535446,0.02036712,-0.00471520,-0.00234563,-0.00938781,-0.01286733,0.03945930,0.00688149,-0.05651744,0.05873454,-0.07248326,-0.00328730,-0.02933591,-0.01863950,0.02716506,-0.01997808,-0.01082392,-0.05753245,0.00722150,0.03949457,0.01390539,0.03001538,0.01532816,-0.01989687,0.02918116,0.03301297,-0.00130497,0.02032712,-0.00059420,0.07596609]',E'Naming event handler props {/*naming-event-handler-props*/}\n\nMake sure that you use the appropriate HTML tags for your event handlers. For example, to handle clicks, use [`<button onClick={handleClick}>`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/button) instead of `<div onClick={handleClick}>`. Using a real browser `<button>` enables built-in browser behaviors like keyboard navigation. If you don''t like the default browser styling of a button and want to make it look more like a link or a different UI element, you can achieve it with CSS','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Responding To Events", "section_title": "responding-to-events", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/responding-to-events.md", "topics": "react,hooks,responding,to,events", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
