8920134,0.05002655,0.02111202,0.00396892,0.00012585,0.01431570,0.03211848,-0.01683356,-0.00066373,-0.06910071,0.05158440,0.00770373,-0.00961797,-0.04972100,-0.00371185,0.01046904,0.02094906,-0.03124463,-0.04916470,0.04800111,0.04014377,-0.05853815,0.06045703,-0.10487751,0.00079319,-0.00504609,0.01451441,0.05324427,0.00051384,-0.04055325,0.04375281,-0.03092524,0.03150256,0.06852485,0.01620251,-0.02680149,0.00043047,0.02370364,0.07708579,-0.00675872,0.03782890,0.01801248,0.05715012]',E'Preventing default behavior {/*preventing-default-behavior*/}\n\nSome browser events have default behavior associated with them. For example, a `<form>` submit event, which happens when a button inside of it is clicked, will reload the whole page by default:\n\n<Sandpack>\n\n```js\nexport default function Signup() {\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={() => alert(''Submitting!'')}>\n      <input />\n      <button>Send</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n```css\nbutton { margin-left: 5px; }\n```\n\n</Sandpack>','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Responding To Events", "section_title": "responding-to-events", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/responding-to-events.md", "topics": "react,hooks,responding,to,events", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
