693,0.16545638,0.04487960,0.04232437,-0.01961699,-0.01192714,0.00225955,0.08572681,0.06209708,-0.00695224,-0.00511173,0.01679312,0.02054698,-0.03096911,-0.04472277,-0.01868344,0.03031944,0.00019358,0.01255977,-0.00530595,0.03104944,0.03162327,0.01024485,0.05000053,-0.03021705,-0.02201605,-0.03957845,-0.09398147,0.01263289,-0.03207890,0.01084331,0.00031853,-0.03052042,0.01659152,0.02234943,-0.04367993,-0.00004318,-0.00972827,0.05292948,0.05788532,0.04302291,0.06396620,-0.00646778,0.00085556]',E'What are Effects and how are they different from events? {/*what-are-effects-and-how-are-they-different-from-events*/}\n\nBefore getting to Effects, you need to be familiar with two types of logic inside React components:\n\n- **Rendering code** (introduced in [Describing the UI](/learn/describing-the-ui)) lives at the top level of your component. This is where you take the props and state, transform them, and return the JSX you want to see on the screen. [Rendering code must be pure.](/learn/keeping-components-pure) Like a math formula, it should only _calculate_ the result, but not do anything else.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
