791059,0.03702733,0.02626160,-0.02082912,-0.03830210,0.01418686,0.05316361,0.02808215,-0.01642037,-0.02643205,0.03213370,0.00450369,0.00648205,-0.05646527,-0.01395009,0.04368129,-0.00925126,0.01424783,-0.00383259,0.03798096,0.05141378,-0.01195225,0.07072499,-0.00300749,-0.01548909,-0.01081427,-0.03405952,0.01611210,0.00119015,-0.02317858,-0.00555795,0.02695699,-0.00377454,0.02670068,-0.04885989,-0.03667751,0.01730683,0.09839004,0.09513856,0.03275803,0.05243895,0.01283105,0.01803958]',E'What are Effects and how are they different from events? {/*what-are-effects-and-how-are-they-different-from-events*/}\n\n***Effects* let you specify side effects that are caused by rendering itself, rather than by a particular event.** Sending a message in the chat is an *event* because it is directly caused by the user clicking a specific button. However, setting up a server connection is an *Effect* because it should happen no matter which interaction caused the component to appear. Effects run at the end of a [commit](/learn/render-and-commit) after the screen updates','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
