226,0.00948670,0.04289817,-0.02074985,-0.00366533,-0.00459193,0.08453037,-0.00583950,-0.02975566,-0.01388847,0.01740556,0.00722282,0.00721501,-0.05380264,-0.03753468,0.04466825,-0.02570595,0.02012507,0.01866827,0.00350192,0.05794100,-0.00264038,0.03321279,-0.02013714,0.01023440,0.02021234,-0.12960449,0.00140386,-0.05340389,0.01204376,0.03172146,-0.02719624,-0.01450340,0.05220638,-0.04019817,0.04209329,0.01196650,0.03100869,0.03943769,0.01353346,0.08509672,0.00986144,0.07025955]',E'Step 1: Declare an Effect {/*step-1-declare-an-effect*/}\n\nBy wrapping the DOM update in an Effect, you let React update the screen first. Then your Effect runs.\n\nWhen your `VideoPlayer` component renders (either the first time or if it re-renders), a few things will happen. First, React will update the screen, ensuring the `<video>` tag is in the DOM with the right props. Then React will run your Effect. Finally, your Effect will call `play()` or `pause()` depending on the value of `isPlaying`.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
