66,0.02869473,0.04430940,-0.02307345,0.02260247,0.01360147,0.07560138,0.04815874,0.00827487,0.01370212,0.01526194,0.04486329,0.04369730,-0.05443512,-0.02476322,0.04943185,0.01610771,0.02501084,-0.01881284,0.02696814,0.09052806,-0.01027893,0.03571534,-0.02289326,-0.03511098,-0.01015245,-0.08761397,0.04796720,-0.07082675,0.02856196,0.03636540,-0.03187656,-0.00057282,0.02355774,-0.06253441,0.00332468,0.02593001,0.04954405,0.03921988,0.01808055,0.09112788,-0.01304362,0.01081066]',E'Step 1: Declare an Effect {/*step-1-declare-an-effect*/}\n\nEffects run as a *result* of rendering. Setting state *triggers* rendering. Setting state immediately in an Effect is like plugging a power outlet into itself. The Effect runs, it sets the state, which causes a re-render, which causes the Effect to run, it sets the state again, this causes another re-render, and so on.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
