7,0.08128683,0.01175414,0.01208874,-0.02858809,0.04214697,0.03596330,0.02265618,-0.08725262,-0.04199076,0.01137755,-0.03646822,0.01036255,-0.05452241,-0.02229029,0.01434385,0.02712266,-0.02094108,-0.05119414,0.06005544,0.03884964,-0.00737337,0.05530545,-0.03764787,0.00128342,-0.00913208,-0.04995994,0.00970257,-0.03816694,-0.02121348,0.05979406,-0.04106540,-0.02786870,0.01676240,-0.01432777,-0.02188908,0.00139767,0.01225781,0.08036382,0.00716728,0.03546398,0.01420792,0.03525104]',E'Don''t use refs to prevent Effects from firing {/*dont-use-refs-to-prevent-effects-from-firing*/}\n\nA common pitfall for preventing Effects firing twice in development is to use a `ref` to prevent the Effect from running more than once. For example, you could "fix" the above bug with a `useRef`:\n\n```js {1,3-4}\n  const connectionRef = useRef(null);\n  useEffect(() => {\n    // 🚩 This wont fix the bug!!!\n    if (!connectionRef.current) {\n      connectionRef.current = createConnection();\n      connectionRef.current.connect();\n    }\n  }, []);\n```','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
