.18370932,0.01768688,-0.00579891,-0.03086135,0.01540640,-0.03567567,0.07485101,-0.02004039,-0.02501445,0.05288981,0.00421308,0.05045947,-0.00727609,-0.02053223,-0.04168997,0.02021767,-0.00597186,0.01558097,-0.06305992,0.03197869,0.07069787,-0.06094893,0.01754242,-0.05427063,-0.04663258,0.04229158,-0.05405854,0.05703701,-0.04064143,0.02208645,0.05390478,-0.04212424,-0.02781631,0.08824126,-0.07795005,0.04586599,0.01106333,0.03078581,0.06073059,0.00248292,0.02330127,-0.03294136,0.01348876]',E'Triggering animations {/*triggering-animations*/}\n\nIf your Effect animates something in, the cleanup function should reset the animation to the initial values:\n\n```js {4-6}\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const node = ref.current;\n  node.style.opacity = 1; // Trigger the animation\n  return () => {\n    node.style.opacity = 0; // Reset to the initial value\n  };\n}, []);\n```\n\nIn development, opacity will be set to `1`, then to `0`, and then to `1` again. This should have the same user-visible behavior as setting it to `1` directly, which is what would happen in production. If you use a third-party animation library with support for tweening, your cleanup function should reset the timeline to its initial state.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
