73225,0.06193144,-0.01127220,0.05001044,-0.08550955,-0.00076018,0.00290234,-0.00362299,-0.04823366,-0.04362127,0.00766848,0.00587356,0.05080125,0.02035523,0.00667527,0.01833895,0.02796342,-0.03348047,-0.04396510,0.02604426,0.01291806,0.02255869,0.03520786,-0.05977276,0.00723199,-0.04970962,-0.02923488,0.01010319,-0.02780292,0.02835824,0.02182282,-0.05243353,0.01611142,0.05101097,-0.03272283,-0.00843160,0.00681591,0.01942001,0.07430174,0.02969954,0.04262042,-0.00643385,0.01853825]',E'What are good alternatives to data fetching in Effects? {/*what-are-good-alternatives-to-data-fetching-in-effects*/}\n\n- **Fetching directly in Effects makes it easy to create "network waterfalls".** You render the parent component, it fetches some data, renders the child components, and then they start fetching their data. If the network is not very fast, this is significantly slower than fetching all data in parallel.\n- **Fetching directly in Effects usually means you don''t preload or cache data.** For example, if the component unmounts and then mounts again, it would have to fetch the data again.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
