4471668,0.04890982,0.00306958,-0.01074609,-0.01267650,-0.04478037,-0.00076201,0.04737407,-0.00772136,-0.01507956,0.04702404,0.02650007,0.03000364,-0.03998652,0.04239372,0.00336590,0.02116402,0.01648293,-0.00939619,0.07189813,0.02295555,0.02191377,0.06427290,-0.07330471,-0.00570561,-0.00974193,-0.03974730,0.00038794,0.00883784,0.01083471,-0.03028115,-0.06355236,-0.03230895,0.01373888,-0.02031386,-0.01050138,0.00374577,0.03539003,0.07804522,0.02576126,0.04436040,-0.07259053,0.09011320]',E'Focus a field on mount {/*focus-a-field-on-mount*/}\n\n<Solution>\n\nCalling `ref.current.focus()` during render is wrong because it is a *side effect*. Side effects should either be placed inside an event handler or be declared with `useEffect`. In this case, the side effect is _caused_ by the component appearing rather than by any specific interaction, so it makes sense to put it in an Effect.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
