094336,0.04031530,-0.02453047,-0.00659641,-0.00966015,-0.01364067,0.04873721,0.03326284,-0.02488854,0.00652289,0.03964290,0.00782915,-0.00177166,-0.05289705,0.04136327,0.01665100,0.00152941,0.00051231,-0.02468814,0.06165526,-0.00280103,0.02426586,0.07896529,-0.09839924,-0.01189304,-0.04349190,-0.09311036,0.03011241,0.01005565,0.00889481,0.01784229,-0.07370188,-0.01681540,0.03126981,-0.03533495,-0.02110462,-0.01760017,0.00524659,0.05003589,0.01663061,0.03998105,-0.08430451,0.09218214]',E'Focus a field on mount {/*focus-a-field-on-mount*/}\n\nTo fix the mistake, wrap the `ref.current.focus()` call into an Effect declaration. Then, to ensure that this Effect runs only on mount rather than after every render, add the empty `[]` dependencies to it.\n\n<Sandpack>\n\n```js src/MyInput.js active\nimport { useEffect, useRef } from ''react'';\n\nexport default function MyInput({ value, onChange }) {\n  const ref = useRef(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    ref.current.focus();\n  }, []);','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
