0.21185513,0.06147083,-0.00421895,-0.01298634,-0.02227517,-0.01055043,0.00704452,-0.00932665,-0.05043121,0.03803749,0.02108094,0.02790976,0.00679713,-0.04576961,-0.03366043,0.03158574,0.02927486,-0.01705027,-0.03088503,0.04211212,-0.00251060,0.00603635,0.03469419,-0.07267901,-0.01674829,0.01387939,-0.04178509,0.02816538,-0.01334682,-0.01697556,0.00512312,-0.03249820,0.00684066,0.04800522,-0.07727081,0.02650635,0.00711617,0.08838046,0.02289573,0.00115066,0.02015883,-0.00561991,0.00215444]',E'Fix fetching inside an Effect {/*fix-fetching-inside-an-effect*/}\n\nEach render''s Effect has its own `ignore` variable. Initially, the `ignore` variable is set to `false`. However, if an Effect gets cleaned up (such as when you select a different person), its `ignore` variable becomes `true`. So now it doesn''t matter in which order the requests complete. Only the last person''s Effect will have `ignore` set to `false`, so it will call `setBio(result)`. Past Effects have been cleaned up, so the `if (!ignore)` check will prevent them from calling `setBio`:','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Synchronizing With Effects", "section_title": "synchronizing-with-effects", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/synchronizing-with-effects.md", "topics": "react,hooks,synchronizing,with,effects", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
