.06836773,0.03279795,0.01470157,-0.00950562,0.03185504,0.10979243,0.00820706,-0.03123829,-0.03604059,0.05009232,-0.00140484,-0.03966983,-0.01190026,0.02234066,0.02850682,-0.00806995,-0.05167282,-0.01803465,0.00660953,-0.02425523,0.02015598,0.08215740,-0.00351179,-0.02410954,-0.03593782,-0.08543143,0.01896439,-0.02763391,0.00765529,0.01498878,-0.08618479,0.06114342,-0.02386470,-0.03356851,-0.02405494,-0.01684109,-0.00556604,0.00074819,0.00895093,0.06144184,0.00338275,0.01276309]',E'Adding a ref to your component {/*adding-a-ref-to-your-component*/}\n\n</Sandpack>\n\nThe ref points to a number, but, like [state](/learn/state-a-components-memory), you could point to anything: a string, an object, or even a function. Unlike state, ref is a plain JavaScript object with the `current` property that you can read and modify.\n\nNote that **the component doesn''t re-render with every increment.** Like state, refs are retained by React between re-renders. However, setting state re-renders a component. Changing a ref does not!','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Referencing Values With Refs", "section_title": "referencing-values-with-refs", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/referencing-values-with-refs.md", "topics": "react,hooks,referencing,values,with,refs", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
