18934490,0.02446058,0.03998428,0.06456726,-0.00856416,0.03624712,0.07058646,-0.00255116,-0.01329085,-0.04182492,0.04693802,0.01537527,-0.03995259,-0.01453403,-0.00121575,0.02967222,-0.02466172,0.00299230,-0.03750802,0.00401021,0.05917687,0.00018932,0.08685109,-0.05152427,-0.00327640,-0.03879488,-0.08894135,0.01026252,-0.06368997,-0.01752494,0.00173174,-0.07199544,0.04756766,0.03346602,0.04245653,-0.02137968,-0.04104511,-0.04043858,0.06596130,0.04852116,0.03796918,0.02382437,0.01574892]',E'Best practices for refs {/*best-practices-for-refs*/}\n\nLimitations of React state don''t apply to refs. For example, state acts like a [snapshot for every render](/learn/state-as-a-snapshot) and [doesn''t update synchronously.](/learn/queueing-a-series-of-state-updates) But when you mutate the current value of a ref, it changes immediately:\n\n```js\nref.current = 5;\nconsole.log(ref.current); // 5\n```\n\nThis is because **the ref itself is a regular JavaScript object,** and so it behaves like one.','{"source": "react", "version": "19", "language": "typescript", "title": "Referencing Values With Refs", "section_title": "referencing-values-with-refs", "url": "https://github.com/reactjs/react.dev/blob/main/src/content/learn/referencing-values-with-refs.md", "topics": "react,hooks,referencing,values,with,refs", "categories": "web,typescript,frontend,spa"}');
